            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "According to Wikipedia, **Euler's Identity** is considered a prime example of mathematical elegance due to its profound and concise relationship between fundamental numbers and operations. It is expressed as:\n\n\\[\ne^{i\\pi} + 1 = 0\n\\]\n\nHere:\n- \\(e\\) is Euler’s number (\\( \\approx 2.718\\)), the base of natural logarithms.\n- \\(i\\) is the imaginary unit (\\(i^2 = -1\\)).\n- \\(\\pi\\) (\\(\\approx 3.14159\\)) represents the ratio of a circle’s circumference to its diameter.\n\nThis equation unifies five key constants in mathematics (\\(0, 1, e, i, \\pi\\)) and contains the fundamental operations (\\(+, \\times, \\text{exponentiation}, \\text{equality}\\)) exactly once. It is a special case of Euler's formula, which connects complex exponential functions to trigonometric functions. Many mathematicians, like Benjamin Peirce and Keith Devlin, have praised it as a deeply beautiful theorem.",
